            <p><strong><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/science/2016/nov/18/teenage-girls-wish-for-preservation-after-death-agreed-to-by-court" target="_blank">In Novel Family Law Decision, U.K. High Court Allows Dying Girl to be Cryogenically Frozen</a></strong></p>
            <p>In a groundbreaking ruling, a judge in the U.K. determined that a 14-year-old girl who died of cancer should be allowed to be cryogenically frozen after her death. The ruling specifically provided that the girl’s mother, who supported the girl’s wishes to be frozen, should be the only person allowed to make decisions about disposing of her body. She was estranged from her father, who initially opposed these plans. This case posed a novel question in terms of the intersection of law, science, and parental rights. However, the court ultimately had to address the fundamental issue of what was in the best interests of the child, and concluded that putting this decision in her mother’s hands was best for her.</p>
